Let's compute it step by step. First, factor out 1.5: y = 1.5 [ sinθ + (cosθ - 1) cotθ ] cotθ = cosθ / sinθ, so: y = 1.5 [ sinθ + (cosθ - 1)(cosθ / sinθ) ] = 1.5 [ sinθ + (cos²θ - cosθ)/sinθ ] = 1.5 [ (sin²θ + cos²θ - cosθ)/sinθ ] Again, sin²θ + cos²θ =1: = 1.5 [ (1 - cosθ)/sinθ ] Therefore, y = 1.5 (1 - cosθ)/sinθ So the intersection point on the right edge of the original square is (1.5, 1.5(1 - cosθ)/sinθ ) Similarly, we can find intersection points on the bottom and left edges. For the bottom edge of the original square, y=-1.5, x from -1.5 to 1.5. The rotated square's edge corresponding to the bottom edge is parametrized as: x = 1.5cosθ - t sinθ y = -1.5sinθ + t cosθ Set y=-1.5: -1.5sinθ + t cosθ = -1.5 Solving for t: t cosθ = -1.5 + 1.5sinθ t = (1.5)(sinθ -1)/cosθ Check if t is in [0,1.5]. If so, x = 1.5cosθ - t sinθ = 1.5cosθ - (1.5)(sinθ -1)tanθ = 1.5cosθ -1.5(sinθ tanθ - tanθ) = 1.5cosθ -1.5(sinθ (sinθ / cosθ) - tanθ ) = 1.5cosθ -1.5( (sin²θ / cosθ) - tanθ ) This is getting too complicated.
